    sem2: {
      label: "2nd Semester",
      topics: {
        inorganic_organic_chemistry: {
          name: "Introduction to Inorganic & Organic Chemistry",
          overview: "This topic introduces the inorganic and organic chemistry covered this semester. Inorganic: chemistry, extraction, properties and uses of iron and its alloys and rusting prevention; chemistry and uses of copper; chemistry and allotropy of sulphur; chemistry, preparation, properties, oxides, hydrides and oxoacids of nitrogen; chemistry, properties, allotropy and isotopes of phosphorus; chemistry, structure, preparation, uses, oxides, allotropy and hydrides of oxygen; Group 1A and Group IIA elements including sodium and its compounds; alkaline earth metals including calcium and its compounds; chemistry, synthesis, reactions and isotopes of hydrogen; Group IVA elements (carbon and silicon); the halogens and their periodic trends and oxoacids; and an introduction to transition metals. Organic: what organic chemistry is and its origin, electron distribution and orbital principles, hybridization (including hybridization of carbon), carbon bonding, ionic and covalent bonds, isomers, homologous series, benzene and its derivatives, amines, aldehydes and ketones, carboxylic acids and their derivatives, amino acids, purification of organic compounds, and qualitative, quantitative, and instrumental methods of structure determination.",
          // Full 200-question bank integrated (CHM001–CHM200).
          // Covers all 12 inorganic + 19 organic subtopics from the syllabus.
          questions: [
          { id: "CHM001", subtopic: "Iron", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Iron is extracted from its ore mainly by which process?", options: ["Electrolysis of molten iron ore", "Reduction in a blast furnace", "Roasting of the ore in air", "Thermal decomposition of the ore"], correct: 1, explain: "Iron is extracted from haematite (Fe2O3) by reduction with carbon monoxide in a blast furnace, not by electrolysis (which is used for very reactive metals like Al)." },
          { id: "CHM002", subtopic: "Iron", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "What is the main ore of iron used in extraction?", options: ["Bauxite (Al2O3), an aluminium ore", "Haematite (Fe2O3)", "Galena (PbS), a lead ore", "Cassiterite (SnO2), a tin ore"], correct: 1, explain: "Haematite (Fe2O3) is the principal iron ore; bauxite is an aluminium ore, galena is lead, cassiterite is tin." },
          { id: "CHM003", subtopic: "Iron", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "In the blast furnace, coke serves primarily to:", options: ["Acting as a flux to remove silica", "Providing carbon monoxide as the reducing agent", "Removing sulphur impurities from the ore", "Cooling the furnace during the reaction"], correct: 1, explain: "Coke burns to form CO2, which reacts with more coke to form CO — the actual reducing agent that converts Fe2O3 to Fe." },
          { id: "CHM004", subtopic: "Iron", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Limestone (CaCO3) is added to the blast furnace to:", options: ["Reducing the ore directly to iron metal", "Acting as a flux, removing silica as slag", "Increasing the furnace's operating temperature", "Providing an additional source of iron"], correct: 1, explain: "Limestone decomposes to CaO, which reacts with silica (SiO2) impurities to form calcium silicate (slag), which is removed separately from the molten iron." },
          { id: "CHM005", subtopic: "Iron", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Which of the following is an alloy of iron?", options: ["Brass, a copper-zinc alloy", "Steel, an iron-carbon alloy", "Bronze, a copper-tin alloy", "Duralumin, an aluminium alloy"], correct: 1, explain: "Steel is an iron-carbon alloy. Brass and bronze are copper alloys; duralumin is an aluminium alloy." },
          { id: "CHM006", subtopic: "Iron", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Stainless steel resists rusting mainly because it contains:", options: ["A zinc coating on the surface", "Chromium and nickel content", "A tin coating on the surface", "Silicon content alone"], correct: 1, explain: "Chromium forms a thin, tough oxide layer on the surface that protects the underlying steel from corrosion; nickel adds further corrosion resistance." },
          { id: "CHM007", subtopic: "Iron", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Rusting of iron is essentially:", options: ["A purely physical change", "An oxidation process requiring both oxygen and moisture", "A reduction process involving loss of oxygen", "A process requiring oxygen alone"], correct: 1, explain: "Rust (hydrated iron(III) oxide) forms when iron reacts with both oxygen and water; either one alone will not cause rusting." },
          { id: "CHM008", subtopic: "Iron", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Which method prevents rusting by making iron the cathode in an electrochemical cell?", options: ["Painting the surface with a coating", "Galvanizing, using zinc for sacrificial protection", "Oiling the surface to exclude air", "Greasing the surface to repel moisture"], correct: 1, explain: "Zinc, being more reactive than iron, corrodes preferentially (sacrificial anode), protecting the iron cathode — this is cathodic protection." },
          { id: "CHM009", subtopic: "Iron", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Cast iron differs from wrought iron mainly in its:", options: ["Surface colour", "Carbon content", "Melting point, being lower for wrought iron", "Magnetic property"], correct: 1, explain: "Cast iron has a high carbon content (~2-4%), making it brittle, while wrought iron has very low carbon content, making it malleable." },
          { id: "CHM010", subtopic: "Iron", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Iron reacts with dilute hydrochloric acid to produce:", options: ["Iron(III) chloride and oxygen gas", "Iron(II) chloride and hydrogen gas", "Iron oxide and water vapour", "No reaction occurring at any temperature"], correct: 1, explain: "Fe + 2HCl → FeCl2 + H2. Dilute acids typically oxidize iron only to the +2 state." },
          { id: "CHM011", subtopic: "Iron", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Which of these is NOT a common use of iron/steel?", options: ["Construction of buildings and bridges", "Manufacture of automobile body panels", "Manufacture of aircraft primary structures", "Manufacture of pipes and machinery"], correct: 2, explain: "Aircraft primary structures use lightweight aluminium alloys, not iron/steel, due to iron's high density." },
          { id: "CHM012", subtopic: "Iron", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "The chemical test to confirm Fe2+ ions in solution uses which reagent to give a green precipitate?", options: ["Sodium hydroxide", "Silver nitrate solution", "Barium chloride solution", "Dilute sulphuric acid"], correct: 0, explain: "NaOH added to a solution containing Fe2+ gives a dirty green precipitate of Fe(OH)2, which darkens on standing as it oxidizes." },
          { id: "CHM013", subtopic: "Copper", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Copper is well suited for electrical wiring mainly because of its:", options: ["High density compared to other metals", "Excellent electrical conductivity and ductility", "Low cost compared to other conductors", "Strong magnetic properties"], correct: 1, explain: "Copper has very high electrical conductivity (second only to silver among common metals) and is ductile enough to be drawn into wires." },
          { id: "CHM014", subtopic: "Copper", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "When copper is heated strongly in air, it forms a black coating of:", options: ["CuCl2 (copper(II) chloride)", "CuO (copper(II) oxide)", "CuSO4 (copper(II) sulphate)", "Cu2O (copper(I) oxide) only"], correct: 1, explain: "2Cu + O2 → 2CuO. The black copper(II) oxide layer forms on the surface when copper is heated in air." },
          { id: "CHM015", subtopic: "Copper", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Copper does not readily react with dilute hydrochloric or sulphuric acid because:", options: ["It is above hydrogen in the reactivity series", "It is below hydrogen in the reactivity series", "It forms a passive oxide layer instantly", "The acids are too dilute to react with any metal"], correct: 1, explain: "Copper is less reactive than hydrogen, so it cannot displace hydrogen from dilute non-oxidizing acids." },
          { id: "CHM016", subtopic: "Copper", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Bronze is an alloy of copper with:", options: ["Zinc", "Tin", "Nickel", "Lead only"], correct: 1, explain: "Bronze is primarily a copper-tin alloy, valued for hardness and corrosion resistance; brass is copper-zinc." },
          { id: "CHM017", subtopic: "Copper", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "The greenish patina that forms on old copper roofs/statues is due to formation of:", options: ["Copper(II) oxide formed by heating in air", "Basic copper carbonate from reaction with CO2, O2 and moisture", "Copper sulphide formed by reaction with sulphur", "Copper nitrate formed by reaction with nitric acid"], correct: 1, explain: "Over time, copper reacts with atmospheric CO2, O2 and water vapour to form a protective green layer of basic copper carbonate, CuCO3·Cu(OH)2." },
          { id: "CHM018", subtopic: "Copper", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Which test confirms Cu2+ ions using excess ammonia solution?", options: ["A white precipitate that dissolves in excess ammonia", "A pale blue precipitate, dissolving to deep blue", "No visible colour change occurring", "A yellow precipitate that remains insoluble"], correct: 1, explain: "Cu2+ + NH3(aq) initially forms pale blue Cu(OH)2, which dissolves in excess ammonia to form the deep blue tetraamminecopper(II) complex ion." },
          { id: "CHM019", subtopic: "Sulphur", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Sulphur exhibits allotropy, existing commonly as:", options: ["Only one crystalline form at all temperatures", "Rhombic (alpha) and monoclinic (beta) sulphur", "Only amorphous, non-crystalline sulphur", "Diamond and graphite forms, as in carbon"], correct: 1, explain: "Rhombic sulphur is stable at room temperature; monoclinic sulphur is stable above about 96°C. Diamond/graphite are allotropes of carbon, not sulphur." },
          { id: "CHM020", subtopic: "Sulphur", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "The molecular formula of the common ring form of sulphur is:", options: ["S2", "S6", "S8", "S4"], correct: 2, explain: "Both rhombic and monoclinic sulphur are composed of puckered S8 ring molecules." },
          { id: "CHM021", subtopic: "Sulphur", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Sulphur burns in oxygen to produce which gas?", options: ["Hydrogen sulphide", "Sulphur dioxide (SO2)", "Sulphur trioxide only", "Sulphuric acid vapour"], correct: 1, explain: "S + O2 → SO2. Sulphur trioxide (SO3) requires a catalyst (as in the Contact Process) and is not the direct product of simple combustion." },
          { id: "CHM022", subtopic: "Sulphur", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Which is a major industrial use of sulphur?", options: ["Manufacture of sulphuric acid", "Manufacture of table salt", "Extraction of aluminium", "Water softening"], correct: 0, explain: "Sulphur is the raw material for sulphuric acid production via the Contact Process, one of the most important industrial chemicals." },
          { id: "CHM023", subtopic: "Sulphur", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Vulcanization of rubber uses sulphur to:", options: ["Bleach the rubber to remove its colour", "Form cross-links between the polymer chains", "Dissolve the rubber into a liquid form", "Colour the rubber black permanently"], correct: 1, explain: "Sulphur atoms form cross-links (bridges) between rubber polymer chains during vulcanization, increasing durability and elasticity." },
          { id: "CHM024", subtopic: "Sulphur", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Monoclinic sulphur crystals are best described as:", options: ["Octahedral and deep yellow in colour", "Long, needle-shaped and pale yellow, stable above 96°C", "Cubic and completely colourless", "Amorphous, non-crystalline, and black"], correct: 1, explain: "Monoclinic sulphur forms needle-like crystals and is the stable form above the transition temperature of about 96°C; below that, rhombic sulphur is stable." },
          { id: "CHM025", subtopic: "Nitrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Nitrogen gas makes up approximately what percentage of the atmosphere by volume?", options: ["21%", "78%", "0.9%", "50%"], correct: 1, explain: "Nitrogen (N2) is the most abundant gas in Earth's atmosphere at about 78% by volume; oxygen is about 21%." },
          { id: "CHM026", subtopic: "Nitrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "In the laboratory, nitrogen gas can be prepared by heating a mixture of:", options: ["Ammonium chloride and sodium hydroxide", "Ammonium chloride and sodium nitrite", "Zinc and dilute acid", "Potassium permanganate alone"], correct: 1, explain: "Heating ammonium chloride with sodium nitrite decomposes to give nitrogen gas, sodium chloride, and water, a common lab preparation route." },
          { id: "CHM027", subtopic: "Nitrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Nitrogen is relatively unreactive at room temperature mainly because of:", options: ["Its comparatively low overall atomic mass", "The strong N≡N triple bond and high bond energy", "Its position within Group 15 of the periodic table", "Its colourless and odourless nature"], correct: 1, explain: "The N≡N triple bond is exceptionally strong (~945 kJ/mol), making N2 kinetically inert at ordinary temperatures despite being thermodynamically reactive with many elements." },
          { id: "CHM028", subtopic: "Nitrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Which oxide of nitrogen is commonly known as 'laughing gas'?", options: ["NO", "NO2", "N2O", "N2O5"], correct: 2, explain: "Nitrous oxide (N2O) is called laughing gas and has historically been used as an anaesthetic." },
          { id: "CHM029", subtopic: "Nitrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Nitrogen dioxide (NO2) is significant environmentally because it:", options: ["Has no measurable atmospheric effect", "Contributes to acid rain and photochemical smog", "Is commonly used to bleach paper pulp", "Forms only in the complete absence of combustion"], correct: 1, explain: "NO2, largely from vehicle and industrial emissions, reacts with water vapour to contribute to acid rain and participates in smog-forming photochemical reactions." },
          { id: "CHM030", subtopic: "Nitrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Ammonia (NH3) is an example of a hydride of nitrogen. Its molecular geometry is:", options: ["A linear geometry", "A trigonal planar geometry", "Trigonal pyramidal geometry", "A tetrahedral geometry"], correct: 2, explain: "NH3 has one lone pair and three bonding pairs around nitrogen, giving a trigonal pyramidal shape (based on tetrahedral electron geometry)." },
          { id: "CHM031", subtopic: "Nitrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Which is the strongest common oxoacid of nitrogen?", options: ["Nitrous acid (HNO2)", "Nitric acid (HNO3)", "Hyponitrous acid", "Both are equally strong"], correct: 1, explain: "Nitric acid (HNO3) is a strong acid, fully ionizing in water, whereas nitrous acid (HNO2) is a weak acid." },
          { id: "CHM032", subtopic: "Nitrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Nitric acid acts as a strong oxidizing agent especially when:", options: ["Dilute and cold", "Concentrated and hot", "Mixed with water only", "Frozen"], correct: 1, explain: "Concentrated hot nitric acid is a powerful oxidizer, capable of reacting with metals below hydrogen in the reactivity series, unlike typical dilute acids." },
          { id: "CHM033", subtopic: "Nitrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Nitrogen is essential to living organisms mainly because it is a key component of:", options: ["Carbohydrates and simple sugars only", "Proteins and nucleic acids", "Lipids and fatty acids only", "Water and other simple inorganic molecules"], correct: 1, explain: "Nitrogen is a core element in amino acids (hence proteins) and in the bases of nucleic acids (DNA/RNA), making it biologically essential." },
          { id: "CHM034", subtopic: "Nitrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Which process converts atmospheric N2 into a usable form for plants industrially?", options: ["Photosynthesis in green plants", "The Haber process (N2 + H2 → NH3)", "The Contact process for sulphuric acid", "Electrolysis of water into hydrogen and oxygen"], correct: 1, explain: "The Haber process combines nitrogen and hydrogen under high pressure/temperature with an iron catalyst to synthesize ammonia for fertilizers." },
          { id: "CHM035", subtopic: "Nitrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Excess nitrogen oxides in the atmosphere primarily contribute to which environmental problem?", options: ["Ozone layer thickening", "Acid rain", "Global cooling", "Increased oxygen levels"], correct: 1, explain: "Nitrogen oxides dissolve in atmospheric moisture to form nitric and nitrous acids, a major contributor to acid rain." },
          { id: "CHM036", subtopic: "Nitrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Nitrous acid (HNO2) is best classified as:", options: ["A strong, thermodynamically stable acid", "A weak, unstable acid that decomposes readily", "A basic compound in aqueous solution", "A neutral, non-acidic compound"], correct: 1, explain: "Nitrous acid is a weak acid and is unstable, readily decomposing (disproportionating) into nitric acid and nitric oxide." },
          { id: "CHM037", subtopic: "Phosphorus", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Phosphorus commonly exists as which two major allotropes?", options: ["Red and white phosphorus", "Blue and green phosphorus", "Grey and pink phosphorus", "Yellow and black phosphorus only"], correct: 0, explain: "White phosphorus (reactive, waxy, toxic) and red phosphorus (less reactive, more stable) are the two most common allotropes." },
          { id: "CHM038", subtopic: "Phosphorus", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "White phosphorus must be stored under water because it:", options: ["Dissolves in water for preservation", "Spontaneously ignites in air", "Reacts with water violently", "Needs to stay cold only"], correct: 1, explain: "White phosphorus is highly reactive and undergoes spontaneous combustion in air, so it is stored under water to exclude oxygen." },
          { id: "CHM039", subtopic: "Phosphorus", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Compared to white phosphorus, red phosphorus is:", options: ["More toxic and chemically reactive", "Less toxic, more stable, and does not glow in the dark", "Identical in all physical and chemical properties", "A liquid at room temperature"], correct: 1, explain: "Red phosphorus has a polymeric structure making it more thermally stable, less reactive, and non-luminescent, unlike white phosphorus." },
          { id: "CHM040", subtopic: "Phosphorus", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Phosphorus is essential biologically mainly as a component of:", options: ["Haemoglobin in red blood cells", "ATP, DNA/RNA, and bone mineral as phosphate", "Chlorophyll found in plant cells", "Vitamin C, also called ascorbic acid"], correct: 1, explain: "Phosphorus, as phosphate, is central to energy transfer (ATP), genetic material (nucleic acid backbones), and bone/tooth mineral (hydroxyapatite)." },
          { id: "CHM041", subtopic: "Phosphorus", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "White phosphorus has the molecular formula:", options: ["P2", "P4", "P8", "P6"], correct: 1, explain: "White phosphorus exists as tetrahedral P4 molecules." },
          { id: "CHM042", subtopic: "Phosphorus", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Phosphorus has naturally occurring isotopes, with the most common stable isotope being:", options: ["P-30", "P-31", "P-32", "P-33"], correct: 1, explain: "Phosphorus-31 is the only stable, naturally occurring isotope of phosphorus (100% natural abundance)." },
          { id: "CHM043", subtopic: "Phosphorus", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Phosphorus-32, a radioactive isotope, is notably used in:", options: ["Water purification processes", "Medical/biological research as a radioactive tracer", "Steel manufacture and refining", "Glass making and processing"], correct: 1, explain: "P-32 is a beta-emitter widely used as a tracer in molecular biology research and in some medical treatments." },
          { id: "CHM044", subtopic: "Phosphorus", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "When phosphorus burns in excess oxygen, it forms:", options: ["Phosphorus(III) oxide only", "Phosphorus(V) oxide, P4O10", "Phosphine gas", "Phosphoric acid directly as a gas"], correct: 1, explain: "In excess oxygen, phosphorus burns to form P4O10 (phosphorus pentoxide), a strong dehydrating agent that reacts with water to form phosphoric acid." },
          { id: "CHM045", subtopic: "Oxygen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "The electronic configuration of oxygen (atomic number 8) is:", options: ["1s2 2s2 2p6", "1s2 2s2 2p4", "1s2 2s2 2p2", "1s2 2s2 2p3"], correct: 1, explain: "Oxygen has 8 electrons: 2 in the 1s orbital, 2 in the 2s orbital, and 4 in the 2p orbitals (1s2 2s2 2p4)." },
          { id: "CHM046", subtopic: "Oxygen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Oxygen typically forms bonds by:", options: ["Losing 2 electrons to form the O2+ ion", "Gaining 2 electrons, or forming 2 covalent bonds", "Never forming any covalent bonds at all", "Only ever forming purely ionic bonds"], correct: 1, explain: "Oxygen needs 2 more electrons to complete its octet, so it typically gains 2 electrons (forming O2-) or forms two covalent bonds (as in H2O)." },
          { id: "CHM047", subtopic: "Oxygen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Oxygen gas can be prepared in the laboratory by heating:", options: ["Sodium chloride dissolved in solution", "Potassium chlorate with a manganese dioxide catalyst", "Calcium carbonate on its own", "Copper sulphate crystals alone"], correct: 1, explain: "Heating KClO3 with MnO2 as a catalyst decomposes it to release oxygen gas: 2KClO3 → 2KCl + 3O2." },
          { id: "CHM048", subtopic: "Oxygen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Which is NOT a common industrial/domestic use of oxygen?", options: ["Supporting combustion in welding (oxy-acetylene)", "Medical/respiratory support", "Steelmaking (removing impurities)", "Refrigeration as a coolant"], correct: 3, explain: "Oxygen is not typically used as a refrigerant; that role is filled by substances like ammonia or fluorinated compounds. Oxygen's key uses relate to combustion, respiration, and steel refining." },
          { id: "CHM049", subtopic: "Oxygen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "The two main allotropes of oxygen are:", options: ["O2 (dioxygen) and O3 (ozone)", "O2 and O4, both diatomic forms", "Only the O2 form exists in nature", "Oxide and peroxide compounds"], correct: 0, explain: "Dioxygen (O2) is the common form we breathe; ozone (O3) is a less stable, more reactive allotrope found in the stratosphere and as a pollutant at ground level." },
          { id: "CHM050", subtopic: "Oxygen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Ozone (O3) in the stratosphere is important because it:", options: ["Increases the global atmospheric oxygen supply", "Absorbs harmful ultraviolet radiation from the sun", "Directly causes acid rain formation", "Has no significant atmospheric or protective role"], correct: 1, explain: "Stratospheric ozone absorbs most of the sun's UV-B and UV-C radiation, protecting living organisms from harmful radiation exposure." },
          { id: "CHM051", subtopic: "Oxygen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Water (H2O) is classified as a hydride of oxygen. Its bond angle is approximately:", options: ["180°", "120°", "104.5°", "90°"], correct: 2, explain: "Water has a bent shape due to two lone pairs on oxygen compressing the H-O-H bond angle to about 104.5°, slightly less than the ideal tetrahedral angle." },
          { id: "CHM052", subtopic: "Oxygen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "An oxide that reacts with both acids and bases is called:", options: ["A basic oxide", "An acidic oxide", "An amphoteric oxide", "A neutral oxide"], correct: 2, explain: "Amphoteric oxides (e.g. Al2O3, ZnO) react with both acids and bases, unlike basic oxides (react with acids only) or acidic oxides (react with bases only)." },
          { id: "CHM053", subtopic: "Oxygen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Hydrogen peroxide (H2O2) is an example of:", options: ["A typical basic metal oxide", "A hydride showing an unusual oxygen oxidation state", "An inert, chemically stable compound", "A pure, uncombined elemental substance"], correct: 1, explain: "In H2O2, oxygen has an oxidation state of -1 (rather than the usual -2), making it a useful oxidizing or reducing agent depending on conditions." },
          { id: "CHM054", subtopic: "Oxygen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "In water, oxygen is bonded to hydrogen through:", options: ["Purely ionic bonds throughout", "Two single covalent bonds, sp3 hybridized oxygen", "A single triple covalent bond", "Metallic-type bonding throughout"], correct: 1, explain: "Oxygen in water forms two polar covalent single bonds with hydrogen atoms, with oxygen adopting approximately sp3 hybridization." },
          { id: "CHM055", subtopic: "Group 1A", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Alkali metals (Group 1A) all have how many electrons in their outermost shell?", options: ["1", "2", "7", "8"], correct: 0, explain: "Group 1A elements (Li, Na, K, Rb, Cs, Fr) each have a single valence electron, which they readily lose to form +1 ions." },
          { id: "CHM056", subtopic: "Group 1A", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Down Group 1A, reactivity of the alkali metals generally:", options: ["Decreases steadily down the whole group", "Increases, as atomic radius grows down the group", "Stays essentially constant down the group", "Becomes negative, which is not physically meaningful"], correct: 1, explain: "As you go down the group, the outer electron is further from the nucleus and more shielded, so it's lost more easily, increasing reactivity." },
          { id: "CHM057", subtopic: "Group 1A", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Alkali metal hydroxides (e.g. NaOH) in water form solutions that are:", options: ["Strongly acidic in aqueous solution", "Strongly basic (alkaline)", "Chemically neutral in solution", "Only weakly acidic"], correct: 1, explain: "Group 1A hydroxides are strong bases, fully dissociating in water to release OH- ions, producing highly alkaline solutions." },
          { id: "CHM058", subtopic: "Group 1A", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Alkali metal halides (e.g. NaCl) are generally characterized by:", options: ["Covalent bonding with comparatively low melting points", "Ionic bonding, high melting points, and solubility in water", "General insolubility in water", "Metallic-type bonding throughout"], correct: 1, explain: "The large electronegativity difference between alkali metals and halogens produces ionic compounds with high melting points that dissolve well in polar solvents like water." },
          { id: "CHM059", subtopic: "Group 1A", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Sodium is industrially extracted by:", options: ["Reduction of its ore with carbon", "Electrolysis of molten sodium chloride (Downs process)", "Roasting its ore in air", "Displacement by a more reactive metal, potassium"], correct: 1, explain: "Sodium is too reactive to be extracted by carbon reduction, so it is obtained by electrolysis of molten NaCl in the Downs process." },
          { id: "CHM060", subtopic: "Group 1A", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Freshly cut sodium metal is stored under oil because it:", options: ["Is denser than the surrounding water", "Reacts rapidly with oxygen and moisture in air", "Needs to be kept warm to remain stable", "Is a radioactive element"], correct: 1, explain: "Sodium is highly reactive and tarnishes/reacts quickly on exposure to air and moisture, so it's stored under an inert liquid like paraffin oil." },
          { id: "CHM061", subtopic: "Group 1A", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Sodium reacts with cold water to produce:", options: ["Sodium oxide and oxygen gas", "Sodium hydroxide and hydrogen gas", "No observable reaction occurring", "Sodium hydride as the sole product"], correct: 1, explain: "2Na + 2H2O → 2NaOH + H2. This is a vigorous, exothermic reaction, often producing enough heat to melt the sodium." },
          { id: "CHM062", subtopic: "Group 1A", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "A key property of sodium hydroxide (NaOH) is that it is:", options: ["Deliquescent (absorbs moisture from air)", "Essentially insoluble in water", "A weak, poorly dissociating base", "Non-corrosive to skin and materials"], correct: 0, explain: "NaOH readily absorbs moisture from the atmosphere (deliquescence) and is highly corrosive and soluble in water." },
          { id: "CHM063", subtopic: "Group 1A", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "A major industrial use of sodium hydroxide is in:", options: ["Manufacture of soap and paper products", "Fuel production, and nothing else", "Manufacture of inert gases only", "Food preservation, and nothing else"], correct: 0, explain: "NaOH is widely used in soap-making (saponification of fats), the paper/pulp industry, and other chemical manufacturing processes." },
          { id: "CHM064", subtopic: "Group 1A", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Sodium peroxide (Na2O2) is used industrially mainly for:", options: ["Bleaching and providing oxygen for breathing apparatus", "Fuel combustion processes exclusively", "Water softening treatments exclusively", "Glass manufacturing exclusively"], correct: 0, explain: "Na2O2 reacts with water/CO2 to release oxygen, making it useful in submarine/spacecraft breathing systems, and it also acts as a bleaching agent." },
          { id: "CHM065", subtopic: "Group 1A", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Sodium chloride (NaCl) forms which type of crystal lattice?", options: ["Molecular lattice", "Face-centred cubic ionic lattice", "Hexagonal covalent lattice", "Amorphous structure"], correct: 1, explain: "NaCl crystallizes in a face-centred cubic (rock salt) ionic lattice, with each Na+ surrounded by 6 Cl- ions and vice versa." },
          { id: "CHM066", subtopic: "Group 1A", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Which alkali metal is the least reactive?", options: ["Caesium (Cs)", "Lithium (Li)", "Potassium (K)", "Sodium (Na)"], correct: 1, explain: "Lithium, at the top of Group 1A, has the smallest atomic radius and highest ionization energy in the group, making it the least reactive alkali metal." },
          { id: "CHM067", subtopic: "Group IIA", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Alkaline earth metals (Group IIA) have how many valence electrons?", options: ["1", "2", "3", "8"], correct: 1, explain: "Group IIA elements (Be, Mg, Ca, Sr, Ba, Ra) each have two valence electrons, which they lose to form +2 ions." },
          { id: "CHM068", subtopic: "Group IIA", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Compared to Group IA metals, Group IIA metals are generally:", options: ["More reactive than Group IA metals", "Less reactive, harder, and denser", "Identical in reactivity to Group IA", "Non-metallic in character"], correct: 1, explain: "Group IIA metals have higher ionization energies (two electrons to remove) and stronger metallic bonding, making them harder, denser, and less reactive than Group IA." },
          { id: "CHM069", subtopic: "Group IIA", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Group IIA hydroxides, compared to Group IA hydroxides, are generally:", options: ["More soluble in water", "Less soluble in water", "Equally soluble", "Insoluble entirely, with no exceptions"], correct: 1, explain: "Group IIA hydroxides (e.g. Mg(OH)2, Ca(OH)2) are considerably less soluble than Group IA hydroxides like NaOH, due to higher lattice energies." },
          { id: "CHM070", subtopic: "Group IIA", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Calcium reacts with water:", options: ["Violently, in a manner similar to sodium", "Moderately, forming calcium hydroxide and hydrogen gas", "Not at all, showing no observable reaction", "Only when it is reacted with steam"], correct: 1, explain: "Ca + 2H2O → Ca(OH)2 + H2, but the reaction is less vigorous than with alkali metals since calcium is less reactive." },
          { id: "CHM071", subtopic: "Group IIA", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Calcium carbonate (CaCO3), a key calcium compound, decomposes on strong heating to form:", options: ["Calcium metal and oxygen gas", "Calcium oxide (quicklime) and carbon dioxide", "Calcium hydroxide formed directly", "Elemental calcium and carbon"], correct: 1, explain: "CaCO3 → CaO + CO2 on strong heating (thermal decomposition), a reaction central to cement and lime production." },
          { id: "CHM072", subtopic: "Group IIA", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Calcium hydroxide solution (limewater) is commonly used to test for the presence of:", options: ["The presence of oxygen gas", "Carbon dioxide gas, turning cloudy/milky", "The presence of hydrogen gas", "The presence of nitrogen gas"], correct: 1, explain: "CO2 reacts with limewater to form insoluble CaCO3, turning the solution milky/cloudy — a standard qualitative test for CO2." },
          { id: "CHM073", subtopic: "Group IIA", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Group IA halides are generally more soluble than the corresponding Group IIA halides, EXCEPT:", options: ["This statement is always true, without exception", "Solubility trends vary by specific compound and anion", "Group IIA halides are never soluble in water", "Group IA halides are never soluble in water"], correct: 1, explain: "Solubility trends between the two groups are compound-specific; while there are general patterns, blanket rules oversimplify actual solubility behavior, which depends on lattice and hydration energies." },
          { id: "CHM074", subtopic: "Group IIA", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "A key difference between Group IA and Group IIA elements is that Group IIA oxides are generally:", options: ["More acidic in character than Group IA oxides", "More strongly basic, due to higher ionic charge density", "Not basic in character at all, remaining neutral", "Gaseous at room temperature and normal pressure"], correct: 1, explain: "Group IIA oxides (e.g. MgO, CaO) form strong ionic lattices with higher melting points than Group IA oxides, due to the +2 charge increasing lattice energy." },
          { id: "CHM075", subtopic: "Hydrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Hydrogen gas can be synthesized in the laboratory by reacting:", options: ["Copper metal reacting with a dilute acid", "A reactive metal, e.g. zinc, with dilute acid", "Sodium chloride dissolved in water", "Oxygen gas mixed with nitrogen gas"], correct: 1, explain: "Zn + 2HCl → ZnCl2 + H2 is a classic laboratory method for preparing hydrogen gas." },
          { id: "CHM076", subtopic: "Hydrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Hydrogen gas burns in oxygen (or air) to produce:", options: ["Only heat, with no chemical products formed", "Water (H2O), releasing energy", "Hydrogen peroxide as the sole product", "Ozone gas"], correct: 1, explain: "2H2 + O2 → 2H2O. This highly exothermic reaction is used, for example, in rocket fuel and the 'pop test' for hydrogen gas." },
          { id: "CHM077", subtopic: "Hydrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Hydrogen has three known isotopes: protium, deuterium, and:", options: ["Helium-3", "Tritium", "Lithium-7", "Neon-20"], correct: 1, explain: "Protium (1H, no neutrons), deuterium (2H, one neutron), and tritium (3H, two neutrons, radioactive) are the three isotopes of hydrogen." },
          { id: "CHM078", subtopic: "Hydrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "All isotopes of hydrogen have the same number of:", options: ["Neutrons", "Protons and electrons", "Protons only, but different electrons", "Mass number"], correct: 1, explain: "Isotopes of the same element always share the same number of protons (and, when neutral, electrons); they differ in neutron number and therefore mass." },
          { id: "CHM079", subtopic: "Hydrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Deuterium differs from protium mainly in that it:", options: ["Has one additional proton in its nucleus", "Has one extra neutron, making it about twice as heavy", "Has one additional electron in its shell", "Is radioactive, while protium is stable"], correct: 1, explain: "Deuterium has 1 proton and 1 neutron, compared to protium's 1 proton and 0 neutrons, roughly doubling its atomic mass." },
          { id: "CHM080", subtopic: "Hydrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Ionic hydrides (e.g. NaH) are formed when hydrogen reacts with:", options: ["Non-metals, such as chlorine gas", "Reactive metals like sodium, forming the H- ion", "Noble gases, which are largely unreactive", "Other hydrogen atoms exclusively"], correct: 1, explain: "With very reactive metals, hydrogen can act as an oxidizing agent, gaining an electron to form the hydride ion H-, as in NaH." },
          { id: "CHM081", subtopic: "Hydrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Covalent hydrides, such as those formed with carbon, nitrogen, or oxygen, are characterized by:", options: ["Complete transfer of electrons between atoms", "Shared electron pairs between hydrogen and the other element", "Metallic-type bonding throughout", "The complete absence of any bonding"], correct: 1, explain: "In covalent hydrides like CH4, NH3, and H2O, hydrogen shares electrons with the other atom rather than fully transferring them." },
          { id: "CHM082", subtopic: "Hydrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Tritium is unique among hydrogen isotopes because it is:", options: ["Stable and the most abundant", "Radioactive, undergoing beta decay", "Not actually an isotope of hydrogen", "Heavier than deuterium's mass by a factor of 10"], correct: 1, explain: "Tritium (3H) is radioactive, decaying via beta emission with a half-life of about 12.3 years, unlike the stable protium and deuterium." },
          { id: "CHM083", subtopic: "Hydrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Hydrogen is the most abundant element in the universe primarily because:", options: ["It was artificially created in laboratories", "It formed abundantly during the early universe", "It forms readily only under Earth conditions", "It is the heaviest of the stable elements"], correct: 1, explain: "Hydrogen, being the lightest and simplest element, was produced in vast quantities during Big Bang nucleosynthesis, making it the most abundant element cosmically." },
          { id: "CHM084", subtopic: "Hydrogen", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Which of the following best describes hydrogen's position in the periodic table?", options: ["It fits perfectly and exclusively into Group 1A", "It shares properties with both Group 1A and VIIA", "It belongs exclusively to Group VIIA elements", "It has no clearly defined group placement"], correct: 1, explain: "Hydrogen can lose one electron (like alkali metals) or gain one electron (like halogens) to complete a shell, giving it a dual/borderline character in classification." },
          { id: "CHM085", subtopic: "Group IVA", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Group IVA elements have how many valence electrons?", options: ["2", "4", "6", "8"], correct: 1, explain: "Group IVA elements (C, Si, Ge, Sn, Pb) each have 4 valence electrons, allowing them to form up to 4 covalent bonds." },
          { id: "CHM086", subtopic: "Group IVA", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Carbon exhibits allotropy, with well-known allotropes including:", options: ["Only graphite, with no other forms", "Diamond, graphite, and fullerenes", "Only diamond, with no other forms", "Carbon exhibits no allotropy at all"], correct: 1, explain: "Carbon exists in several structural forms — diamond (tetrahedral, hard), graphite (layered, soft, conductive), and fullerenes (cage-like molecules such as C60)." },
          { id: "CHM087", subtopic: "Group IVA", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "In diamond, each carbon atom is bonded to how many other carbon atoms?", options: ["2", "3", "4", "6"], correct: 2, explain: "Diamond has a tetrahedral network structure where each carbon atom forms 4 strong covalent bonds to neighbouring carbon atoms, giving diamond its extreme hardness." },
          { id: "CHM088", subtopic: "Group IVA", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Graphite conducts electricity, unlike diamond, because:", options: ["It contains trace amounts of metal impurities", "Each carbon has a delocalized, mobile electron", "It is significantly denser than diamond", "It exhibits purely ionic-type bonding"], correct: 1, explain: "In graphite, each carbon bonds to only 3 others, leaving one delocalized electron per atom that can move freely within the layer, allowing conduction." },
          { id: "CHM089", subtopic: "Group IVA", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Silicon's bonding and structure closely resemble which allotrope of carbon?", options: ["Graphite, with its layered structure", "Diamond (giant covalent, tetrahedral structure)", "Fullerene, a spherical carbon cage", "Amorphous carbon (soot)"], correct: 1, explain: "Silicon, also having 4 valence electrons, forms a diamond-like giant covalent tetrahedral lattice, though it is a semiconductor rather than an insulator." },
          { id: "CHM090", subtopic: "Group IVA", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Silicon's most important modern application is in:", options: ["Jewelry making and decoration", "Semiconductors and computer chips", "Food preservation processes", "Textile dyeing processes"], correct: 1, explain: "Silicon's semiconducting properties make it the foundational material of modern electronics, including transistors and integrated circuits." },
          { id: "CHM091", subtopic: "Halogens", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Halogens (Group VIIA) are characterized by having how many valence electrons?", options: ["5", "6", "7", "8"], correct: 2, explain: "Halogens have 7 valence electrons, needing just one more to complete their octet, which makes them highly reactive non-metals." },
          { id: "CHM092", subtopic: "Halogens", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Reactivity of halogens generally _______ down the group.", options: ["Increases", "Decreases", "Stays the same", "Becomes zero"], correct: 1, explain: "Unlike metals, halogen reactivity decreases down the group because the increasing atomic radius makes it harder to attract an extra electron to complete the octet." },
          { id: "CHM093", subtopic: "Halogens", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "At room temperature, chlorine exists as a:", options: ["A solid at room temperature", "A liquid at room temperature", "A greenish-yellow gas", "A colourless, odourless gas"], correct: 2, explain: "Chlorine is a greenish-yellow, toxic gas at room temperature, while bromine is a liquid and iodine is a solid, illustrating the trend in physical state down the group." },
          { id: "CHM094", subtopic: "Halogens", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Fluorine is unique among halogens in being:", options: ["The least reactive of all the halogens", "The most electronegative and reactive halogen", "A metallic, non-halogen element", "Essentially non-existent in nature"], correct: 1, explain: "Fluorine has the highest electronegativity of all elements and is the most reactive halogen, reacting vigorously with nearly all other elements." },
          { id: "CHM095", subtopic: "Halogens", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Iodine at room temperature is a solid that, when heated gently, undergoes:", options: ["Melting directly into a liquid only", "Sublimation, forming a violet vapour", "No physical change occurring at all", "Spontaneous combustion"], correct: 1, explain: "Iodine sublimes readily on gentle heating, passing directly from solid to a distinctive violet-coloured gas without melting." },
          { id: "CHM096", subtopic: "Halogens", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Astatine, the rarest naturally occurring halogen, is notable for being:", options: ["Highly abundant and chemically stable", "Radioactive and extremely rare in nature", "A liquid at room temperature used industrially", "Completely non-reactive chemically"], correct: 1, explain: "Astatine is intensely radioactive with a short half-life, occurring only in trace amounts in nature, making it one of the rarest elements on Earth." },
          { id: "CHM097", subtopic: "Halogens", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "A displacement reaction where chlorine displaces bromine from a bromide solution demonstrates that:", options: ["Bromine is more reactive than chlorine here", "Chlorine is more reactive than bromine in Group VIIA", "The two halogens are exactly equally reactive", "No such displacement reaction is ever possible"], correct: 1, explain: "Cl2 + 2NaBr → 2NaCl + Br2 occurs because chlorine, being above bromine, is more reactive and displaces it from solution." },
          { id: "CHM098", subtopic: "Halogens", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Halogen oxoacids increase in acid strength with increasing oxidation state of the halogen, e.g. among chlorine's oxoacids, the strongest is:", options: ["Hypochlorous acid (HOCl)", "Chlorous acid (HClO2)", "Chloric acid (HClO3)", "Perchloric acid (HClO4)"], correct: 3, explain: "Among Cl oxoacids, acid strength increases with the number of oxygen atoms/oxidation state: HOCl < HClO2 < HClO3 < HClO4, making perchloric acid the strongest." },
          { id: "CHM099", subtopic: "Transition Metals", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Transition metals are generally defined as elements that:", options: ["Have completely filled d-orbitals always", "Have an incompletely filled d-subshell in the atom or ion", "Belong exclusively to Group 1A and 2A", "Never form any coloured compounds"], correct: 1, explain: "The defining feature of transition metals is a partially filled d-subshell (in the atom or a stable ion), which underlies properties like variable oxidation states and coloured compounds." },
          { id: "CHM100", subtopic: "Transition Metals", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "A characteristic property common to most transition metals is:", options: ["Formation of colourless compounds exclusively", "Forming coloured compounds and acting as catalysts", "Uniformly low melting points across the board", "Non-metallic character throughout the group"], correct: 1, explain: "Transition metals typically show multiple oxidation states, form coloured complexes/compounds due to d-d electron transitions, and are widely used as catalysts (e.g. Fe in the Haber process)." },
          { id: "CHM101", subtopic: "Intro to Organic Chemistry", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Organic chemistry is best defined as the study of:", options: ["All chemical reactions occurring in living things only", "Carbon compounds, typically bonded to hydrogen", "Only compounds that occur naturally in nature", "Purely metallic and inorganic compounds"], correct: 1, explain: "Organic chemistry is the branch of chemistry dealing with carbon-containing compounds, most of which also contain hydrogen, and often oxygen, nitrogen, or other elements." },
          { id: "CHM102", subtopic: "Intro to Organic Chemistry", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Which of these is NOT typically classified as an organic compound?", options: ["Methane (CH4)", "Ethanol (C2H5OH)", "Carbon dioxide (CO2)", "Glucose (C6H12O6)"], correct: 2, explain: "CO2 and a few other simple carbon compounds (carbonates, cyanides, carbides) are conventionally classified as inorganic despite containing carbon." },
          { id: "CHM103", subtopic: "Intro to Organic Chemistry", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Carbon's ability to form the vast diversity of organic compounds is mainly due to its ability to:", options: ["Form only single covalent bonds always", "Catenate, forming long chains and rings", "React exclusively with oxygen gas", "Exist only in the gaseous state"], correct: 1, explain: "Catenation, carbon's unique ability to bond extensively with other carbon atoms to form chains, branches, and rings, underlies the enormous variety of organic compounds." },
          { id: "CHM104", subtopic: "Intro to Organic Chemistry", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Organic compounds, compared to most inorganic compounds, typically have:", options: ["Higher melting points and are mostly ionic", "Lower melting/boiling points and are mostly covalent", "Identical properties to inorganic salts", "No carbon content"], correct: 1, explain: "Because organic compounds are largely covalent with weaker intermolecular forces, they generally have lower melting and boiling points than ionic inorganic compounds." },
          { id: "CHM105", subtopic: "Origin of Organic Chemistry", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "The term 'organic chemistry' historically arose from the belief that organic compounds:", options: ["Could only ever be synthesized in a laboratory", "Could only be produced by living organisms", "Contained absolutely no carbon", "Were always gaseous substances"], correct: 1, explain: "Early chemists believed a 'vital force' present only in living organisms was required to produce organic compounds, hence the name." },
          { id: "CHM106", subtopic: "Origin of Organic Chemistry", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Which historic experiment is credited with disproving the vital force theory?", options: ["Lavoisier's early combustion experiments", "Wöhler's synthesis of urea from ammonium cyanate (1828)", "Dalton's early atomic theory", "Rutherford's gold foil scattering experiment"], correct: 1, explain: "In 1828, Friedrich Wöhler synthesized urea, an organic compound, from ammonium cyanate, an inorganic starting material, showing organic compounds don't require a 'vital force' to form." },
          { id: "CHM107", subtopic: "Origin of Organic Chemistry", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Following Wöhler's synthesis, the definition of organic chemistry shifted to focus on:", options: ["Compounds made only by living things", "The chemistry of carbon compounds generally", "Only compounds with a vital force", "Compounds without hydrogen"], correct: 1, explain: "After the vital force theory was disproved, organic chemistry was redefined simply as the study of carbon-based compounds, regardless of origin." },
          { id: "CHM108", subtopic: "Electron Distribution", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Electrons are distributed into atomic orbitals following the Aufbau principle, which states that:", options: ["Electrons fill higher energy orbitals first", "Electrons occupy the lowest available energy orbitals first", "All orbitals fill simultaneously", "Electrons avoid all orbitals equally"], correct: 1, explain: "The Aufbau ('building up') principle states electrons fill orbitals starting from the lowest energy level and progressing upward." },
          { id: "CHM109", subtopic: "Electron Distribution", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "The Pauli Exclusion Principle states that:", options: ["No two electrons in an atom can have the same set of four quantum numbers", "Electrons must always pair up immediately upon entering an orbital", "Orbitals can hold an unlimited number of electrons", "Electrons strongly repel protons within the nucleus"], correct: 0, explain: "The Pauli Exclusion Principle means each electron in an atom has a unique quantum number combination; consequently, an orbital can hold a maximum of 2 electrons with opposite spins." },
          { id: "CHM110", subtopic: "Electron Distribution", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Hund's Rule states that electrons filling orbitals of equal energy (degenerate orbitals) will:", options: ["Pair up in the same orbital first before spreading out", "Occupy separate orbitals singly before pairing", "Never occupy any p orbitals at all", "Always remain permanently unpaired"], correct: 1, explain: "Hund's Rule states that electrons individually occupy each degenerate orbital (e.g. each of the three 2p orbitals) before any pairing occurs, minimizing electron-electron repulsion." },
          { id: "CHM111", subtopic: "Electron Distribution", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "The maximum number of electrons that can occupy the second principal energy level (n=2) is:", options: ["2", "8", "18", "32"], correct: 1, explain: "Using 2n², for n=2, the maximum is 2(2)² = 8 electrons, distributed among the 2s and 2p subshells." },
          { id: "CHM112", subtopic: "Electron Distribution", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "A p subshell contains how many orbitals, and thus can hold a maximum of how many electrons?", options: ["1 orbital, 2 electrons", "3 orbitals, 6 electrons", "5 orbitals, 10 electrons", "7 orbitals, 14 electrons"], correct: 1, explain: "A p subshell has 3 orbitals (px, py, pz), each holding up to 2 electrons, giving a maximum capacity of 6 electrons." },
          { id: "CHM113", subtopic: "Orbital Occupation Principles", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Which three principles together govern how electrons occupy atomic orbitals?", options: ["Newton's three laws of motion", "Aufbau, Pauli Exclusion, and Hund's Rule", "Boyle's law and Charles's law of gases", "Avogadro's law of gases alone"], correct: 1, explain: "Together, these three principles determine electron configuration: Aufbau (order of filling), Pauli (max 2 electrons per orbital, opposite spin), and Hund's rule (singly occupy degenerate orbitals first)." },
          { id: "CHM114", subtopic: "Orbital Occupation Principles", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Orbitals are filled in order of increasing energy, which is generally approximated using the:", options: ["Periodic table trend only", "n+l rule (Madelung's rule)", "Reactivity series", "Bond length order"], correct: 1, explain: "The n+l rule (Madelung's rule) predicts the relative order in which subshells fill, explaining phenomena like 4s filling before 3d despite the lower principal quantum number of 3d." },
          { id: "CHM115", subtopic: "Orbital Occupation Principles", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Why does the 4s orbital fill before the 3d orbital, despite 3 being a lower principal quantum number?", options: ["4s has lower energy than 3d in the neutral atom according to the n+l rule", "3d orbitals do not exist in any atom", "It is simply a random exception with no underlying basis", "4s electrons are physically heavier than 3d electrons"], correct: 0, explain: "Using the n+l rule, 4s has n+l = 4+0 = 4, while 3d has n+l = 3+2 = 5. Since 4 < 5, 4s is filled first in most neutral atoms." },
          { id: "CHM116", subtopic: "Orbital Occupation Principles", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Electron configuration principles help predict which key property of atoms relevant to organic chemistry?", options: ["The nuclear mass of the atom only", "Bonding behavior and valence electron arrangement", "The colour of the resulting compound only", "Physical state at room temperature only"], correct: 1, explain: "Understanding electron distribution, especially valence electrons, is essential for predicting how atoms like carbon bond and hybridize in organic molecules." },
          { id: "CHM117", subtopic: "Hybrid Orbitals", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Hybridization is best described as:", options: ["The mixing of atomic orbitals to form hybrid orbitals", "The loss of electrons from an atom entirely", "A specific, unrelated type of nuclear reaction", "The splitting of molecules into individual atoms"], correct: 0, explain: "Hybridization is a theoretical model where atomic orbitals (e.g. s and p) mix to form new hybrid orbitals of equal energy, which better explain observed molecular geometries." },
          { id: "CHM118", subtopic: "Hybrid Orbitals", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "An sp3 hybrid orbital is formed from the mixing of:", options: ["One s and three p orbitals", "Three s and one p orbital", "Two s and two p orbitals", "One s and one p orbital only"], correct: 0, explain: "sp3 hybridization mixes one s orbital with three p orbitals to form four equivalent hybrid orbitals arranged tetrahedrally." },
          { id: "CHM119", subtopic: "Hybrid Orbitals", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "sp2 hybrid orbitals are arranged in which geometric shape?", options: ["A linear geometric arrangement", "A trigonal planar arrangement", "A tetrahedral arrangement", "An octahedral arrangement"], correct: 1, explain: "sp2 hybridization (one s + two p orbitals) produces three hybrid orbitals arranged in a trigonal planar geometry, at 120° to each other." },
          { id: "CHM120", subtopic: "Hybrid Orbitals", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "sp hybridization results in what molecular geometry?", options: ["Tetrahedral", "Trigonal planar", "Linear", "Bent"], correct: 2, explain: "sp hybridization (one s + one p orbital) produces two hybrid orbitals arranged linearly, 180° apart." },
          { id: "CHM121", subtopic: "Hybrid Orbitals", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Unhybridized p orbitals remaining after sp2 hybridization are involved in forming:", options: ["Sigma bonds exclusively", "Pi (π) bonds, as seen in double bonds", "Ionic bonds between atoms", "No bonds of any kind"], correct: 1, explain: "After sp2 hybridization uses up two p orbitals, the remaining unhybridized p orbital overlaps sideways with a neighbouring p orbital to form a pi bond, as in C=C double bonds." },
          { id: "CHM122", subtopic: "Hybridization", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Hybridization theory helps explain why carbon, with the ground-state configuration 1s2 2s2 2p2, can form:", options: ["Only 2 covalent bonds", "4 equivalent bonds, as in methane (CH4)", "No covalent bonds whatsoever", "Only ionic bonds"], correct: 1, explain: "Without hybridization, carbon's ground state would suggest only 2 unpaired electrons for bonding; hybridization (promoting an electron and mixing orbitals) explains carbon's characteristic 4 bonds." },
          { id: "CHM123", subtopic: "Hybridization", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "A sigma (σ) bond is formed by:", options: ["Sideways overlap of p orbitals only", "Head-on overlap of orbitals along the bond axis", "Overlap of d orbitals exclusively", "No orbital overlap occurring at all"], correct: 1, explain: "Sigma bonds form from direct, head-on overlap of orbitals along the internuclear axis, allowing free rotation around a single bond." },
          { id: "CHM124", subtopic: "Hybridization", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "A pi (π) bond, found in double and triple bonds, is characterized by:", options: ["Head-on orbital overlap along the bond axis", "Sideways overlap of unhybridized p orbitals", "Being inherently stronger than sigma bonds", "Occurring exclusively in single bonds"], correct: 1, explain: "Pi bonds form from sideways overlap of parallel p orbitals above and below the bond axis, restricting rotation and generally being weaker than sigma bonds." },
          { id: "CHM125", subtopic: "Hybridization", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "A carbon-carbon triple bond (as in alkynes) consists of:", options: ["Three pi bonds and no sigma bonds", "One sigma bond and two pi bonds", "Three sigma bonds and no pi bonds", "One pi bond and no sigma bonds"], correct: 1, explain: "A triple bond is made of one sigma bond (head-on overlap) plus two pi bonds (from the two remaining unhybridized p orbitals in sp-hybridized carbon)." },
          { id: "CHM126", subtopic: "Hybridization of Carbon", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "In methane (CH4), the carbon atom is:", options: ["sp hybridized", "sp2 hybridized", "sp3 hybridized", "Not hybridized"], correct: 2, explain: "Carbon in methane forms 4 single bonds arranged tetrahedrally, consistent with sp3 hybridization." },
          { id: "CHM127", subtopic: "Hybridization of Carbon", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "In ethene (CH2=CH2), each carbon atom is:", options: ["sp hybridized", "sp2 hybridized", "sp3 hybridized", "sp3d hybridized"], correct: 1, explain: "Each carbon in ethene forms 3 sigma bonds (2 to H, 1 to C) in a trigonal planar arrangement — sp2 hybridization — with the remaining p orbital forming the pi bond of the double bond." },
          { id: "CHM128", subtopic: "Hybridization of Carbon", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "In ethyne (HC≡CH), each carbon atom is:", options: ["sp hybridized", "sp2 hybridized", "sp3 hybridized", "Not hybridized"], correct: 0, explain: "Each carbon in ethyne forms only 2 sigma bonds (linear arrangement), consistent with sp hybridization, with two remaining p orbitals forming the two pi bonds of the triple bond." },
          { id: "CHM129", subtopic: "Hybridization of Carbon", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "The bond angle in sp3-hybridized carbon (as in methane) is approximately:", options: ["180°", "120°", "109.5°", "90°"], correct: 2, explain: "sp3 hybridized carbon has a tetrahedral electron geometry, giving bond angles of approximately 109.5°." },
          { id: "CHM130", subtopic: "Hybridization of Carbon", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "As hybridization changes from sp3 to sp2 to sp, the carbon-carbon bond length:", options: ["Increases progressively with each change", "Decreases progressively from single to triple bonds", "Stays exactly the same in every case", "Becomes entirely unpredictable each time"], correct: 1, explain: "Increasing s-character (sp3 → sp2 → sp) pulls bonding electrons closer to the nucleus, shortening bond length: C-C (154 pm) > C=C (134 pm) > C≡C (120 pm)." },
          { id: "CHM131", subtopic: "Carbon Bonding", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Carbon's tetravalency (forming 4 bonds) is explained by it having how many valence electrons after promotion/hybridization?", options: ["2", "3", "4", "6"], correct: 2, explain: "Carbon has 4 valence electrons (2s2 2p2), and through orbital promotion and hybridization, all 4 become available for bonding, giving carbon its characteristic tetravalency." },
          { id: "CHM132", subtopic: "Carbon Bonding", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Carbon atoms can bond to form which structural arrangements?", options: ["Straight chains exclusively", "Straight chains, branched chains, and rings", "Rings exclusively", "Spherical clusters exclusively"], correct: 1, explain: "Carbon's catenation ability allows it to form straight chains, branched structures, and cyclic (ring) compounds, contributing to organic chemistry's vast structural diversity." },
          { id: "CHM133", subtopic: "Carbon Bonding", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "A single bond between two carbon atoms consists of:", options: ["One sigma bond only", "One sigma and one pi bond", "Two sigma bonds", "Two pi bonds"], correct: 0, explain: "A single covalent bond, such as C-C, is always a single sigma bond formed by direct orbital overlap." },
          { id: "CHM134", subtopic: "Carbon Bonding", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Free rotation around a carbon-carbon bond is possible for:", options: ["Single (sigma) bonds, but restricted for double bonds", "Double bonds exclusively", "Triple bonds exclusively", "All bond types equally, without restriction"], correct: 0, explain: "Because sigma bonds have cylindrical symmetry along the bond axis, rotation doesn't break orbital overlap. Pi bonds, however, require specific orbital alignment, restricting rotation." },
          { id: "CHM135", subtopic: "Carbon Bonding", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Carbon rarely forms ionic bonds in organic compounds mainly because:", options: ["It favors electron sharing over ion formation", "It possesses no valence electrons at all", "It behaves chemically as a metallic element", "It always exists as a free, isolated ion"], correct: 0, explain: "Losing or gaining 4 electrons to form C4+ or C4- ions is energetically unfavourable; carbon instead shares electrons through covalent bonding." },
          { id: "CHM136", subtopic: "Ionic and Covalent Bonds", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "An ionic bond is formed through:", options: ["Sharing of electron pairs between atoms", "Complete transfer of electrons, forming charged ions", "Overlap of p orbitals exclusively", "Metallic-type electron delocalization"], correct: 1, explain: "Ionic bonding involves the transfer of one or more electrons from a metal to a non-metal, creating oppositely charged ions held together by electrostatic attraction." },
          { id: "CHM137", subtopic: "Ionic and Covalent Bonds", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "A covalent bond is formed through:", options: ["Complete transfer of electrons between atoms", "Mutual sharing of electron pairs between atoms", "Complete loss of all valence electrons", "Electrostatic attraction between ions only"], correct: 1, explain: "In covalent bonding, atoms share one or more pairs of electrons, allowing each atom to attain a more stable electron configuration." },
          { id: "CHM138", subtopic: "Ionic and Covalent Bonds", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Organic compounds are predominantly held together by:", options: ["Ionic bonds", "Covalent bonds", "Metallic bonds", "Hydrogen bonds only, with no covalent bonds"], correct: 1, explain: "Because carbon and the elements it typically bonds with (H, O, N) have similar electronegativities, organic compounds are almost exclusively covalent." },
          { id: "CHM139", subtopic: "Ionic and Covalent Bonds", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "A polar covalent bond arises when:", options: ["Two atoms share electrons in a perfectly equal manner", "Unequal electron sharing due to electronegativity difference", "No electrons are shared between the atoms at all", "The bond is entirely ionic in character"], correct: 1, explain: "When atoms of different electronegativity share electrons, the shared pair is pulled closer to the more electronegative atom, creating partial charges (a polar bond), as in C-O or O-H bonds." },
          { id: "CHM140", subtopic: "Ionic and Covalent Bonds", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Compared to ionic compounds, covalent organic compounds generally have:", options: ["Higher melting points and conduct electricity well when molten", "Lower melting/boiling points and poor electrical conductivity", "Identical solubility behavior in water", "No distinguishing properties"], correct: 1, explain: "Weaker intermolecular forces (van der Waals, hydrogen bonding) between covalent molecules result in lower melting/boiling points and generally poor electrical conductivity, unlike ionic compounds." },
          { id: "CHM141", subtopic: "Isomers", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Isomers are defined as compounds that have:", options: ["The same molecular formula but different structural arrangements", "Different molecular formulas but an identical structure", "Identical physical and chemical properties in every respect", "No structural or compositional relationship to each other"], correct: 0, explain: "Isomers share the same molecular formula (same number and type of atoms) but differ in how those atoms are arranged, leading to different properties." },
          { id: "CHM142", subtopic: "Isomers", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Structural (constitutional) isomers differ in:", options: ["3D spatial arrangement only, with identical connectivity", "The actual connectivity/bonding sequence of atoms", "Nothing — they are identical compounds", "Molecular formula"], correct: 1, explain: "Structural isomers have atoms connected in different orders/patterns, resulting in genuinely different compounds, e.g. butane vs. isobutane." },
          { id: "CHM143", subtopic: "Isomers", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Chain isomerism arises from differences in:", options: ["The position of a functional group on the chain", "The carbon skeleton, straight chain vs branched", "The type of functional group present only", "3D spatial orientation of atoms only"], correct: 1, explain: "Chain isomers have the same molecular formula but different carbon chain arrangements, e.g. n-butane (straight) vs. 2-methylpropane (branched)." },
          { id: "CHM144", subtopic: "Isomers", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Positional isomerism occurs when compounds differ in:", options: ["The carbon skeleton alone, with no other change", "The position of a group on an identical carbon skeleton", "Their overall molecular formula changes entirely", "The type of bonding present (ionic vs covalent)"], correct: 1, explain: "Positional isomers, such as 1-propanol and 2-propanol, have identical carbon skeletons and functional groups but differ in where the functional group is attached." },
          { id: "CHM145", subtopic: "Isomers", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Functional group isomerism occurs when compounds with the same molecular formula have:", options: ["Identical functional groups throughout", "Different functional groups, e.g. alcohol vs ether", "The same carbon chain length only", "No functional groups present at all"], correct: 1, explain: "Functional group isomers share a molecular formula but belong to different classes of compounds, such as ethanol (C2H6O, an alcohol) and dimethyl ether (C2H6O, an ether)." },
          { id: "CHM146", subtopic: "Isomers", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Stereoisomers have the same molecular formula and connectivity, but differ in:", options: ["The actual bonding sequence of atoms", "The 3D spatial arrangement of atoms", "The number of atoms present", "Their elemental composition"], correct: 1, explain: "Stereoisomers are structurally identical (same connectivity) but differ in how atoms are arranged in 3D space, as seen in cis-trans (geometric) and optical isomers." },
          { id: "CHM147", subtopic: "Isomers", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Cis-trans (geometric) isomerism arises due to restricted rotation around which type of bond?", options: ["A single (sigma) bond alone", "A double bond (or ring structure)", "An ionic bond between atoms", "A hydrogen bond between molecules"], correct: 1, explain: "Because rotation around a C=C double bond is restricted (breaking the pi bond would be required), substituents can be locked into cis (same side) or trans (opposite side) arrangements." },
          { id: "CHM148", subtopic: "Homologous Series", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "A homologous series is best described as a group of compounds that:", options: ["Have completely unrelated structures and properties", "Share the same general formula, differing by -CH2- each time", "Have exactly identical molecular formulas throughout", "Contain no carbon atoms in their structure"], correct: 1, explain: "Members of a homologous series follow a general formula and share chemical properties due to a common functional group, with each successive member differing by one -CH2- unit." },
          { id: "CHM149", subtopic: "Homologous Series", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "The general formula for the alkane homologous series is:", options: ["CnH2n", "CnH2n+2", "CnH2n-2", "CnH2n+1OH"], correct: 1, explain: "Alkanes (saturated hydrocarbons) follow the general formula CnH2n+2, e.g. methane CH4 (n=1), ethane C2H6 (n=2)." },
          { id: "CHM150", subtopic: "Homologous Series", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "The general formula for the alkene homologous series is:", options: ["CnH2n+2", "CnH2n", "CnH2n-2", "CnHn"], correct: 1, explain: "Alkenes, containing one C=C double bond, follow the general formula CnH2n." },
          { id: "CHM151", subtopic: "Homologous Series", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Within a homologous series, as the number of carbon atoms increases, boiling points generally:", options: ["Decrease steadily with chain length", "Increase steadily, due to increasing van der Waals forces", "Remain essentially constant", "Fluctuate in a random, unpredictable manner"], correct: 1, explain: "Longer carbon chains have more surface area for van der Waals (London dispersion) interactions, so boiling points generally rise with increasing chain length within a series." },
          { id: "CHM152", subtopic: "Homologous Series", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Members of the same homologous series show similar chemical properties mainly because they share:", options: ["The same molecular mass", "The same functional group", "The same physical state at room temperature", "Identical melting points"], correct: 1, explain: "The functional group largely dictates chemical reactivity, so compounds in the same homologous series (sharing that group) behave similarly in reactions, even as physical properties like boiling point vary with chain length." },
          { id: "CHM153", subtopic: "Benzene", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Benzene has the molecular formula:", options: ["C6H12", "C6H6", "C6H14", "C5H5"], correct: 1, explain: "Benzene, the parent aromatic hydrocarbon, has the molecular formula C6H6, with a ring of 6 carbon atoms." },
          { id: "CHM154", subtopic: "Benzene", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "The bonding in benzene is best described as:", options: ["Alternating single and double bonds, fixed rigidly in place", "A delocalized system of pi electrons spread evenly over all 6 carbon atoms", "Purely single bonds with no pi-electron character", "Ionic-type bonding between the ring carbons"], correct: 1, explain: "Rather than fixed alternating bonds, benzene's 6 p-electrons are delocalized in a ring of electron density above and below the plane of carbon atoms, giving all C-C bonds equal length (intermediate between single and double)." },
          { id: "CHM155", subtopic: "Benzene", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Benzene's delocalized structure gives it what characteristic compared to a hypothetical 'cyclohexatriene'?", options: ["Lower stability and greater reactivity", "Extra stability from delocalization, reducing reactivity", "Identical reactivity to cyclohexatriene", "A higher melting point, with no other change"], correct: 1, explain: "Delocalization spreads electron density evenly, lowering the molecule's overall energy and making benzene notably more stable and less reactive toward addition reactions than a simple triene would be." },
          { id: "CHM156", subtopic: "Benzene", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Benzene typically undergoes which type of reaction rather than addition reactions?", options: ["Electrophilic substitution", "Nucleophilic addition", "Elimination only", "Reduction only"], correct: 0, explain: "Because addition would destroy its stable delocalized pi system, benzene preferentially undergoes electrophilic substitution, retaining the aromatic ring while replacing a hydrogen." },
          { id: "CHM157", subtopic: "Benzene", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Toluene (methylbenzene) is an example of a benzene derivative where:", options: ["A hydrogen atom is replaced by a methyl group", "The benzene ring is broken open entirely", "Two separate rings are fused together", "All hydrogen atoms are replaced simultaneously"], correct: 0, explain: "Toluene is benzene with one hydrogen substituted by a -CH3 (methyl) group, a simple monosubstituted aromatic compound." },
          { id: "CHM158", subtopic: "Benzene", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Phenol, a benzene derivative, has which functional group attached to the ring?", options: ["-COOH", "-OH", "-NH2", "-CHO"], correct: 1, explain: "Phenol is benzene with a hydroxyl (-OH) group directly attached to the aromatic ring, giving it distinct acidic properties compared to typical alcohols." },
          { id: "CHM159", subtopic: "Benzene", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "When benzene undergoes nitration, the electrophile involved is:", options: ["Cl+ (chloronium-type ion)", "NO2+ (nitronium ion)", "SO3 (sulphur trioxide)", "Br+ (bromonium-type ion)"], correct: 1, explain: "In nitration, concentrated nitric and sulphuric acids generate the nitronium ion (NO2+), the electrophile that attacks the benzene ring in electrophilic substitution." },
          { id: "CHM160", subtopic: "Amines", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Amines are organic derivatives of which inorganic compound?", options: ["Water", "Ammonia (NH3)", "Carbon dioxide", "Hydrogen chloride"], correct: 1, explain: "Amines are formed by replacing one, two, or three hydrogen atoms of ammonia (NH3) with alkyl or aryl groups." },
          { id: "CHM161", subtopic: "Amines", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "A primary amine has the general structure:", options: ["R-NH2, with one alkyl/aryl group attached to nitrogen", "R2NH, with two alkyl/aryl groups attached to nitrogen", "R3N, with three alkyl/aryl groups attached to nitrogen", "R4N+, with four alkyl/aryl groups attached to nitrogen"], correct: 0, explain: "Primary amines (R-NH2) have one carbon-containing group bonded to the nitrogen; secondary (R2NH) have two, and tertiary (R3N) have three." },
          { id: "CHM162", subtopic: "Amines", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Amines are basic in nature primarily because:", options: ["The nitrogen lone pair can accept a proton", "They contain an oxygen atom in their structure", "They possess no lone pairs of electrons", "They are always positively charged species"], correct: 0, explain: "The lone pair on the nitrogen atom in amines can accept H+ (act as a Brønsted base), which is why amines typically behave as weak bases." },
          { id: "CHM163", subtopic: "Amines", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Primary amines can be prepared in the laboratory by reduction of which compound class?", options: ["Reduction of alcohols", "Nitro compounds or nitriles", "Reduction of carboxylic acids directly", "Reduction of alkanes"], correct: 1, explain: "Reduction of nitro compounds (R-NO2) or nitriles (R-CN) is a standard laboratory route to primary amines." },
          { id: "CHM164", subtopic: "Amines", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Lower molecular weight amines are typically characterized by:", options: ["No odour at all", "A distinctive fishy or ammonia-like odour", "Being solids at room temperature", "Being completely insoluble in water"], correct: 1, explain: "Small amines like methylamine and trimethylamine have a characteristic fishy/ammonia-like smell and are generally soluble in water due to hydrogen bonding." },
          { id: "CHM165", subtopic: "Aldehydes and Ketones", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Both aldehydes and ketones contain which functional group?", options: ["-OH, the hydroxyl group", "The carbonyl group, C=O", "-COOH, the carboxyl group", "-NH2, the amino group"], correct: 1, explain: "Aldehydes and ketones both share the carbonyl functional group (C=O); they differ in what is attached to the carbonyl carbon." },
          { id: "CHM166", subtopic: "Aldehydes and Ketones", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "The key structural difference between an aldehyde and a ketone is that an aldehyde has:", options: ["At least one hydrogen atom directly attached to the carbonyl carbon", "Two alkyl/aryl groups attached to the carbonyl carbon", "No hydrogen atoms present anywhere in the molecule", "An -OH group in place of the C=O group"], correct: 0, explain: "In aldehydes, the carbonyl carbon is bonded to at least one hydrogen (R-CHO), while in ketones, it is bonded to two carbon-containing groups (R-CO-R')." },
          { id: "CHM167", subtopic: "Aldehydes and Ketones", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Which test distinguishes aldehydes from ketones based on aldehydes' ability to reduce Cu2+ to Cu2O?", options: ["The bromine water decolourization test", "Fehling's test (or Tollens' test)", "The litmus paper test", "The iodine solution test"], correct: 1, explain: "Fehling's solution (or Tollens' reagent) is reduced by aldehydes, giving a brick-red precipitate of Cu2O (Fehling's) or a silver mirror (Tollens'), but ketones generally do not react." },
          { id: "CHM168", subtopic: "Aldehydes and Ketones", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Aldehydes are generally more reactive than ketones toward nucleophilic addition because:", options: ["Ketones possess no carbonyl group whatsoever", "Ketones have bulkier alkyl groups, increasing steric hindrance", "Aldehydes lack a carbonyl group in their structure", "Aldehydes are always much larger in molecular size"], correct: 1, explain: "Ketones' two alkyl groups sterically hinder nucleophilic attack and also electronically stabilize the carbonyl carbon (reducing its partial positive charge) more than aldehydes' single alkyl/H group." },
          { id: "CHM169", subtopic: "Aldehydes and Ketones", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "The simplest aldehyde, methanal (formaldehyde), has the structure:", options: ["CH3CHO", "HCHO", "CH3COCH3", "CH3CH2CHO"], correct: 1, explain: "Methanal (formaldehyde), HCHO, is the simplest aldehyde, with the carbonyl carbon bonded to two hydrogen atoms." },
          { id: "CHM170", subtopic: "Aldehydes and Ketones", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "The simplest ketone, propanone (acetone), has the structure:", options: ["CH3CHO", "CH3COCH3", "HCHO", "CH3CH2OH"], correct: 1, explain: "Propanone (acetone), CH3COCH3, is the simplest ketone, with the carbonyl carbon flanked by two methyl groups." },
          { id: "CHM171", subtopic: "Aldehydes and Ketones", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Aldehydes and ketones can both be reduced to form:", options: ["Carboxylic acids, in every case", "Alcohols (primary from aldehydes, secondary from ketones)", "Alkanes directly, with no intermediate step", "Esters exclusively, with no exceptions"], correct: 1, explain: "Reduction (e.g. with NaBH4 or LiAlH4) converts the carbonyl C=O to C-OH: aldehydes yield primary alcohols, and ketones yield secondary alcohols." },
          { id: "CHM172", subtopic: "Carboxylic Acids", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Carboxylic acids contain which characteristic functional group?", options: ["-COOH (carboxyl group)", "-OH, the hydroxyl group only", "-CHO, the aldehyde group", "-CO-, the ketone linkage"], correct: 0, explain: "Carboxylic acids are defined by the carboxyl group, -COOH, which combines a carbonyl (C=O) and a hydroxyl (-OH) on the same carbon." },
          { id: "CHM173", subtopic: "Carboxylic Acids", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Carboxylic acids are weak acids because in water they:", options: ["Fully and completely ionize in solution", "Only partially ionize, reaching an equilibrium", "Fail entirely to dissolve in water", "Act as strong bases instead of acids"], correct: 1, explain: "Unlike strong mineral acids, carboxylic acids only partially dissociate in water, releasing H+ and forming an equilibrium with the carboxylate ion (RCOO-)." },
          { id: "CHM174", subtopic: "Carboxylic Acids", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "The simplest carboxylic acid, methanoic acid (formic acid), has the formula:", options: ["CH3COOH", "HCOOH", "C2H5COOH", "CH3CH2CH2COOH"], correct: 1, explain: "Methanoic acid (formic acid), HCOOH, is the simplest carboxylic acid, with just one carbon." },
          { id: "CHM175", subtopic: "Carboxylic Acid Derivatives", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "An ester is formed when a carboxylic acid reacts with an alcohol in a reaction called:", options: ["Hydrolysis, breaking the ester bond", "Esterification (condensation, releasing water)", "An oxidation reaction", "A reduction reaction"], correct: 1, explain: "Esterification is the condensation reaction between a carboxylic acid and an alcohol (usually acid-catalyzed), producing an ester and water." },
          { id: "CHM176", subtopic: "Carboxylic Acid Derivatives", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "An acid chloride (acyl chloride) is a carboxylic acid derivative where the -OH is replaced by:", options: ["-NH2", "-Cl", "-OR", "-OCOR"], correct: 1, explain: "Acyl chlorides (e.g. CH3COCl) are formed by replacing the -OH of a carboxylic acid with -Cl, making them highly reactive acylating agents." },
          { id: "CHM177", subtopic: "Carboxylic Acid Derivatives", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "An amide is a carboxylic acid derivative characterized by the functional group:", options: ["-COOH, the carboxyl group", "-CONH2 (or substituted variants)", "-COOR, the ester group", "-COCl, the acid chloride group"], correct: 1, explain: "Amides contain the -CONH2 functional group (or N-substituted variants), formed for example from the reaction of an acyl chloride or ester with ammonia or an amine." },
          { id: "CHM178", subtopic: "Carboxylic Acid Derivatives", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Among carboxylic acid derivatives, the general order of decreasing reactivity toward nucleophilic acyl substitution is:", options: ["Amide > ester > acid chloride", "Acid chloride > ester > amide", "Amide > acid chloride > ester", "All derivatives react equally"], correct: 1, explain: "Acid chlorides are the most reactive derivatives (best leaving group), followed by esters, with amides being the least reactive due to the strong resonance stabilization of the C-N bond." },
          { id: "CHM179", subtopic: "Amino Acids", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Amino acids are characterized by having both which two functional groups?", options: ["A hydroxyl (-OH) and an aldehyde (-CHO) group", "An amino group (-NH2) and a carboxyl group (-COOH)", "An aldehyde (-CHO) and a carboxyl (-COOH) group", "Two separate hydroxyl (-OH) groups"], correct: 1, explain: "Amino acids contain both a basic amino group (-NH2) and an acidic carboxyl group (-COOH), giving them amphoteric character." },
          { id: "CHM180", subtopic: "Amino Acids", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "In alpha-amino acids, the amino group is located:", options: ["On the carbon furthest from the carboxyl group", "Adjacent to the carboxyl group (the alpha carbon)", "Not attached to any carbon atom at all", "Positioned randomly anywhere in the molecule"], correct: 1, explain: "Alpha-amino acids, the building blocks of proteins, have their amino group attached to the alpha carbon, which is directly bonded to the carboxyl group." },
          { id: "CHM181", subtopic: "Amino Acids", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "At physiological pH, amino acids exist predominantly as:", options: ["Neutral, entirely uncharged molecules only", "Zwitterions, carrying both positive and negative charges", "Purely cationic, positively-charged species", "Purely anionic, negatively-charged species"], correct: 1, explain: "Amino acids exist as zwitterions at their isoelectric point, where the amino group is protonated (-NH3+) and the carboxyl group is deprotonated (-COO-) simultaneously." },
          { id: "CHM182", subtopic: "Amino Acids", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Amino acids link together to form proteins through which type of bond?", options: ["An ester bond linkage", "Peptide bond (amide linkage)", "A glycosidic bond linkage", "Hydrogen bonding alone"], correct: 1, explain: "A peptide bond forms via condensation between the carboxyl group of one amino acid and the amino group of another, releasing water — this is a type of amide linkage." },
          { id: "CHM183", subtopic: "Amino Acids", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "How many amino acids are generally considered the standard building blocks of proteins?", options: ["10", "20", "30", "50"], correct: 1, explain: "There are 20 standard amino acids commonly incorporated into proteins in living organisms, encoded by the genetic code." },
          { id: "CHM184", subtopic: "Amino Acids", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Essential amino acids are those that:", options: ["The body can synthesize entirely on its own", "Must be obtained through the diet, not self-made", "Are not required for protein synthesis at all", "Are found exclusively in plant sources"], correct: 1, explain: "Essential amino acids cannot be synthesized by the human body in adequate amounts and must be supplied through diet, unlike non-essential amino acids." },
          { id: "CHM185", subtopic: "Purification of Organic Compounds", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Recrystallization is a purification technique best suited for purifying:", options: ["Gaseous substances, and nothing else", "Solids, based on differing solubility by temperature", "Liquids with similar boiling points only", "Ionic salts, and nothing else"], correct: 1, explain: "Recrystallization purifies solid compounds by dissolving in a hot solvent, then allowing the pure compound to crystallize out on cooling while impurities remain dissolved." },
          { id: "CHM186", subtopic: "Purification of Organic Compounds", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Distillation is used to separate/purify compounds primarily based on differences in:", options: ["Solubility", "Boiling point", "Colour", "Density alone"], correct: 1, explain: "Distillation separates liquid mixtures by exploiting differences in boiling points; the component with the lower boiling point vaporizes and is collected first." },
          { id: "CHM187", subtopic: "Purification of Organic Compounds", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Chromatography separates mixtures based on differences in:", options: ["Melting point differences and nothing else", "Differing affinities for stationary vs mobile phase", "Colour differences only, with no other basis", "Molecular mass differences exclusively"], correct: 1, explain: "Chromatography separates components based on their differing partition/adsorption between a stationary phase and a moving mobile phase, causing them to travel at different rates." },
          { id: "CHM188", subtopic: "Purification of Organic Compounds", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Solvent extraction is a purification method that relies on:", options: ["Differences in boiling point alone", "Differing solubility in two immiscible solvents", "Melting point differences alone", "Differences in electrical conductivity"], correct: 1, explain: "Solvent extraction separates a compound based on its greater solubility in one of two immiscible solvents (e.g. separating an organic compound from water using an organic solvent)." },
          { id: "CHM189", subtopic: "Purification of Organic Compounds", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "The purity of a recrystallized organic solid is commonly confirmed by:", options: ["Its colour alone, with no further testing", "A sharp melting point matching literature values", "Its characteristic smell, and nothing else", "Its solubility in any solvent whatsoever"], correct: 1, explain: "Pure compounds have a sharp, well-defined melting point; a broad or depressed melting range typically indicates the presence of impurities." },
          { id: "CHM190", subtopic: "Qualitative and Quantitative Analysis", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Qualitative analysis in organic chemistry is primarily concerned with:", options: ["Determining the exact quantity of a substance present", "Identifying functional groups or elements present", "Measuring reaction rates exclusively", "Calculating molecular mass with precision"], correct: 1, explain: "Qualitative analysis focuses on identifying the presence or absence of specific elements, functional groups, or compounds, rather than measuring exact amounts." },
          { id: "CHM191", subtopic: "Qualitative and Quantitative Analysis", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Quantitative analysis in organic chemistry is primarily concerned with:", options: ["Determining unknown functional groups only", "Measuring the precise amount or concentration present", "Observing visual colour changes only", "Structure elucidation, and nothing else"], correct: 1, explain: "Quantitative analysis determines how much of a substance is present, often through techniques like titration or gravimetric analysis." },
          { id: "CHM192", subtopic: "Qualitative and Quantitative Analysis", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Bromine water is commonly used as a qualitative test to detect the presence of:", options: ["The presence of alcohols only", "Unsaturation, C=C bonds, by decolourizing on contact", "The presence of carboxylic acids", "Amines, and nothing else"], correct: 1, explain: "Bromine water is decolourized (orange to colourless) when it reacts with unsaturated compounds like alkenes via addition, making it a standard test for C=C double bonds." },
          { id: "CHM193", subtopic: "Qualitative and Quantitative Analysis", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "In quantitative analysis, titration is commonly used to determine the:", options: ["The melting point of a solid sample", "Concentration of an acid or base in a solution", "The boiling point of a liquid sample", "Molecular structure directly"], correct: 1, explain: "Titration involves gradually adding a solution of known concentration to react completely with an analyte, allowing calculation of the analyte's unknown concentration." },
          { id: "CHM194", subtopic: "Qualitative and Quantitative Analysis", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "A colour-change indicator test to detect a carboxylic acid could use:", options: ["Sodium hydrogen carbonate, releasing CO2 gas", "Bromine water, and nothing else", "Fehling's solution exclusively", "Iodine solution, and nothing else"], correct: 0, explain: "Carboxylic acids react with sodium hydrogen carbonate to release CO2 gas, seen as effervescence — a simple qualitative test to distinguish acids from other functional groups like alcohols." },
          { id: "CHM195", subtopic: "Instrumental Methods", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Infrared (IR) spectroscopy is primarily used to identify:", options: ["The molecular mass of a compound only", "Functional groups, via bond vibration frequencies", "The 3D spatial arrangement of atoms only", "Isotopic composition of a compound"], correct: 1, explain: "IR spectroscopy detects characteristic absorption frequencies corresponding to the vibration (stretching/bending) of specific bonds, allowing identification of functional groups like C=O, O-H, and N-H." },
          { id: "CHM196", subtopic: "Instrumental Methods", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Mass spectrometry primarily provides information about a compound's:", options: ["Functional groups present in the compound only", "Molecular mass and fragmentation pattern of a compound", "Optical activity of the compound alone", "Melting point of the compound alone"], correct: 1, explain: "Mass spectrometry ionizes and fragments a molecule, measuring the mass-to-charge ratio of the resulting ions to determine molecular mass and structural information from the fragmentation pattern." },
          { id: "CHM197", subtopic: "Instrumental Methods", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Nuclear Magnetic Resonance (NMR) spectroscopy provides information about:", options: ["The colour of a compound, and nothing else", "The chemical environment of specific atoms in a molecule", "Only the empirical formula of the compound", "The boiling point of the compound only"], correct: 1, explain: "NMR exploits the magnetic properties of certain nuclei (like 1H and 13C) to reveal detailed information about the chemical environment and connectivity of atoms within a molecule's structure." },
          { id: "CHM198", subtopic: "Instrumental Methods", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Ultraviolet-visible (UV-Vis) spectroscopy is particularly useful for studying compounds containing:", options: ["Saturated bonds only, with no pi systems present", "Conjugated pi-electron systems, as in aromatic rings", "Ionic bonds exclusively, with no covalent character", "Radioactive isotopes present within the compound"], correct: 1, explain: "UV-Vis spectroscopy detects electronic transitions, most notably in molecules with conjugated pi systems (e.g. aromatic compounds, dyes), which absorb characteristically in the UV-visible range." },
          { id: "CHM199", subtopic: "Instrumental Methods", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "In IR spectroscopy, a strong, broad absorption around 3200-3550 cm-1 is most characteristic of:", options: ["A sharp C=O carbonyl stretch", "An O-H or N-H stretch, as in alcohols or amines", "A simple C-H stretch only", "A C≡C triple bond stretch"], correct: 1, explain: "O-H and N-H bonds absorb strongly in this broad region due to hydrogen bonding effects, distinguishing them from the sharper, more specific C=O stretch typically seen around 1650-1750 cm-1." },
          { id: "CHM200", subtopic: "Instrumental Methods", format: "Single Best Answer", stem: "Combining multiple instrumental techniques (IR, NMR, MS) for structure determination is standard practice because:", options: ["A single technique alone gives complete structural information", "Each technique reveals different structural information together", "It is legally required in every analytical case", "Only one technique is ever truly needed"], correct: 1, explain: "No single spectroscopic technique gives a full structural picture; combining complementary data (IR for functional groups, NMR for atom connectivity/environment, MS for molecular mass) allows chemists to confidently deduce a structure." }
          ]
        }
      }
    }
